Egg Rolls were quite good. Sweet & Sour sauce was the best I've ever tasted. My Husbands Hot & Sour soup was good, so too the Crab Rangoon's, though the amount of crab was rather slim, according to him.  Our hope were very high, after reading reviews, and sampling the appetizers. Then our main dishes arrived and everything went downhill fast. The food on each of our plates was tasty, done properly and spiced just perfectly. Truly, was an enjoyable & pleasant experience, until the  "Burned" taste hit the palate.  Some dish, prior, was burned and the pan not cleaned afterwards.  My plate smelled burnt, but was not, while it did have that burnt taste. My Husbands plate simply tasted burnt, without any smell.  Granted, this was late in the lunch hour, after 1pm, and the parking lot was still half full. We pointed out the issue, to our server, who was friendly and apologetic. Rather than allow them to have another go, we decided to leave without a main course.  After realizing that the cooking pans had obviously not been cleaned, well enough if at all, between each use, we started really looking about the place, rather than engaging each other in conversation.  The place was dirty. Just what we could see, out front. The floor, baseboards, even the tables. Tables that had plates on the, when we walked in 20 minutes earlier, still had those same plates sitting.  I can overlook some dirt on the floor, black marks on the baseboard that never get cleaned off, even dust/webs on the ceiling tiles. Some of the very best greasy spoon restaurants have all those things, but the counters are clean, so too the plates and prep surfaces. Just don;t let the lack of cleanliness be tasted, in my food.  While my Husband paid, at the counter, I went off to the ladies room. You guessed it, Dirty & no towels. When I walked over and mentioned this to my Husbands, he asked the cashier for some paper napkins or towels.  She asked him, "Why?" in a rather rude manner. Enough so, that I asked my Husband , "Have you been rude?"  To which he replied, "No". Turning to the Cashier, he informed her that the ladies rest room was out of towels and I needed to dry my hands, after washing them.  She tossed him some napkins. While I was drying my hands, she asked him, more statement than question, "You're not ever coming back here, are you?"  "No", my Husband replied, simply.  This place has many excellent reviews, It could very well be that we just hit them, on a bad day. Though, I doubt it.

I also found the red curry and Thai chicken basil dishes to be bland (despite being overly salted)- not what you'd expect, or want, from flavor-forward Thai cuisine.  (How can a curry dish that is ordered "spicy" be bland?)  I also almost choked on my Diet Coke when I found out they charge almost $3 for a soda.  Despite all this, I probably would have gone back for the pho... with a water.  Today, however, there was a patron who loudly, and rudely, shared his conservative politics; including being against same-sex marriage and overall disparaging liberals, for everyone in the restaurant to hear.  I wouldn't have held a guest's conduct against the restaurant except that I pieced together that the ignorant, loud-mouth was spewing his hatred in his conversation with the restaurant OWNER; who laughed and encouraged the loud ramblings.  When I paid my bill they had fliers for Republican election candidates next to the cash register.  The Republican propaganda and hate speech were worse than the gravy that they pass off as soup.  This liberal, and fan of decent Thai food, won't be going back.
